          },
          "correct": "a",
          "difficulty": "hard",
          "explanation": "Let \\(x = a^{\\frac{1}{2}}\\), then \\(a^{-\\frac{1}{2}} = \\frac{1}{x}\\).\nGiven:\n\\((x + \\frac{1}{x})^2 = 7 \\Rightarrow x^2 + 2 + \\frac{1}{x^2} = 7 \\Rightarrow x^2 + \\frac{1}{x^2} = 5\\)\nBut \\(x^2 = a\\) and \\(\\frac{1}{x^2} = \\frac{1}{a}\\), so:\n\\(a + \\frac{1}{a} = 5\\)."
